  "buggy_functions": [
    "azx_resume",
    "azx_suspend",
    "azx_rirb_get_response",
    "azx_init_chip"
  ],
  "confidence": 0.95,
  "reasoning": "The bug is caused by error recovery state flags (specifically chip->polling_mode and chip->single_cmd) that are set when codec communication timeouts occur in azx_rirb_get_response(), but are never reset during suspend/resume cycles. When chip->polling_mode is set to 1 as an error recovery mechanism (line ~912), this flag persists across suspend (azx_suspend) and resume (azx_resume) operations. The azx_resume function does not reset chip->polling_mode to 0 before reinitializing the hardware, causing the driver to continue using polling mode instead of interrupts after resume. Additionally, when the driver falls back to single_cmd mode (line ~951) due to persistent timeouts, the rirb.cmds[] command tracking array is not cleared, leading to stale command counters that prevent proper communication with the codec. The fix requires resetting the error recovery flags (polling_mode and single_cmd) in the azx_resume function to allow the driver to reattempt normal operation after hardware power cycling. Alternatively, the rirb.cmds array should be properly cleared when switching communication modes."
}

